         key to the wrong host — and it re-labelled all pre-existing spend funding_source=WORKSPACE,
         exempting every existing workspace from the instance budget cap this release ships. Legacy
         configs are intentionally left unbound; LlmModelResolver.legacy() resolves them with the correct
         per-provider defaults and FundingSource.INSTANCE, unchanged from pre-#1368 behaviour. Do not
         reuse id -11 for an unrelated change — ids in this file are append-only history. -->

    <!-- 12. Ledger provenance completion (#1368 slice 6): applied_price_id alone (changeset 9) is a
         live soft ref into llm_model_price — if that row is later superseded, the id still resolves
         but a reader would need to trust its CURRENT rates for a HISTORICAL event, which is wrong the
         moment pricing changes. Freeze the rates actually applied at record time instead, so a dollar
         stays falsifiable regardless of what the catalog looks like today. applied_workspace_model_id
         covers the BYO path, which has no price-history table (workspace_llm_model carries only the
         current inline rate) and so no analogous "price row id" to soft-ref. Both soft refs, no FK:
         the ledger must survive catalog-row deletion (see class doc on llm_usage_event.sourceId). -->
    <changeSet id="1784566728230-12" author="hephaestus">
        <preConditions onFail="MARK_RAN" onFailMessage="llm_usage_event provenance columns already exist">
            <not><columnExists tableName="llm_usage_event" columnName="applied_workspace_model_id"/></not>
        </preConditions>
        <comment>Ledger provenance: applied_workspace_model_id + frozen per-1M rate snapshot (#1368)</comment>
        <addColumn tableName="llm_usage_event">
            <column name="applied_workspace_model_id" type="BIGINT"/>
            <column name="applied_per_1m_input_usd" type="NUMERIC(18,8)"/>
            <column name="applied_per_1m_output_usd" type="NUMERIC(18,8)"/>
            <column name="applied_per_1m_cache_read_usd" type="NUMERIC(18,8)"/>
            <column name="applied_per_1m_cache_write_usd" type="NUMERIC(18,8)"/>
            <column name="applied_per_1m_reasoning_usd" type="NUMERIC(18,8)"/>
        </addColumn>
        <rollback>
            <dropColumn tableName="llm_usage_event" columnName="applied_workspace_model_id"/>
            <dropColumn tableName="llm_usage_event" columnName="applied_per_1m_input_usd"/>
            <dropColumn tableName="llm_usage_event" columnName="applied_per_1m_output_usd"/>
            <dropColumn tableName="llm_usage_event" columnName="applied_per_1m_cache_read_usd"/>
            <dropColumn tableName="llm_usage_event" columnName="applied_per_1m_cache_write_usd"/>
            <dropColumn tableName="llm_usage_event" columnName="applied_per_1m_reasoning_usd"/>
        </rollback>
    </changeSet>

    <!-- 13. Slice 7 (audit wiring): the instance LLM catalog (llm_connection / llm_model /
         instance_llm_settings) is GLOBAL — config_audit_event.workspace_id is NOT NULL, so it cannot
         carry these changes — and is therefore audited on auth_event instead, same ledger
         AccountAdminController already uses for APP_ROLE_CHANGED. Same DROP + ADD shape as
         1782980500800-15: the ADD validates every existing row in one pass under a momentary ACCESS
         EXCLUSIVE lock. -->
    <changeSet id="1784566728230-13" author="hephaestus">
        <preConditions onFail="MARK_RAN" onFailMessage="ck_auth_event_event_type already admits the LLM catalog event types">
            <sqlCheck expectedResult="0">
                SELECT COUNT(*) FROM pg_constraint
                 WHERE conname = 'ck_auth_event_event_type'
                   AND pg_get_constraintdef(oid) LIKE '%LLM_SETTINGS_CHANGED%'
            </sqlCheck>
        </preConditions>
        <comment>Widen ck_auth_event_event_type to admit the instance LLM catalog's audit events (#1368)</comment>
        <sql splitStatements="false"><![CDATA[
            ALTER TABLE auth_event DROP CONSTRAINT ck_auth_event_event_type;
            ALTER TABLE auth_event ADD CONSTRAINT ck_auth_event_event_type CHECK (event_type IN (
                'LOGIN', 'LOGIN_FAILED', 'LOGOUT', 'TOKEN_REFRESH', 'JWT_REVOKED',
                'IDENTITY_LINKED', 'IDENTITY_UNLINKED',
                'IMPERSONATION_BEGIN', 'IMPERSONATION_END',
                'ACCOUNT_DELETED',
                'EXPORT_REQUESTED', 'APP_ROLE_CHANGED',
                'RESEARCH_CONSENT_REVOKED',
                'LLM_CONNECTION_CREATED', 'LLM_CONNECTION_UPDATED', 'LLM_CONNECTION_DELETED',
                'LLM_MODEL_CREATED', 'LLM_MODEL_UPDATED', 'LLM_MODEL_DELETED',
                'LLM_MODEL_PRICE_CHANGED', 'LLM_MODEL_SHARING_CHANGED', 'LLM_SETTINGS_CHANGED'
            ));
        ]]></sql>
        <!-- Empty (#1368 migration-correctness fix): re-adding the narrow CHECK would fail the moment
             any row has been written with one of the new LLM_* event types — a data-preserving downgrade
             is not possible without deleting or remapping those rows, which a rollback must never do
             silently. Rolling back past this changeset means accepting the wider CHECK stays in place. -->
        <rollback/>
    </changeSet>

    <!-- 14. Slice 7 (audit wiring): admit the workspace BYO catalog's two entity types on
         config_audit_event — same DROP + ADD shape as 1784534949268-5 (which added
         WORKSPACE_LLM_BUDGET). The enum and this constraint must stay in lockstep —
         ConfigAuditImmutabilityIntegrationTest reads pg_constraint and fails on drift. -->
    <changeSet id="1784566728230-14" author="hephaestus">
        <preConditions onFail="MARK_RAN" onFailMessage="config_audit_event entity_type CHECK already covers WORKSPACE_LLM_MODEL">
            <sqlCheck expectedResult="0">
